‚ÄúThe love and attention we seek is actually within.‚Äù

Most nights, I spend time thinking about how I am not loved by my friends the way I wanted to be loved. I long for the same things I do for them - random text messages, small piece of chocolates, or even just a five-minute talk about our lives. I always go to the loop of how I always initiate, I always give, I always care for and how the acts of love I give isn‚Äôt the same with what I get. Today, I realized I can do the things I do for others, for myself. I can spend time with just hanging around, listening to music, drawing and writing, buying my favorite candy, and giving myself the kind words I always seek from others. 

I remember a quote I come across, non-verbatim but it sounded like ‚ÄúTalk to yourself as if you were your hurting friend.‚Äù If we can‚Äôt receive it from others, might as well give it to ourselves. No one is going to love us more than ourselves because we know ourselves inside out. It‚Äôs time to care for ourselves, too. ü§ç

Day 25:

You know, I wasn't going to practice today.

I've gotten kinder and more understanding with myself when I miss days, and I've been pretty consistent for the past several.  I woke up stiff all over, and managed to stretch a terrible crick _into_ my back and shoulder, rather than out of it.  Rounding my back twinged like a bad neck  from sleeping upright in a chair.  A few experimental cat-cows, just to try and loosen it up, _hurt_.

But it was the kind of hurt that felt like stretching and loosening up would help instead of make it worse, and I'm better at listening to my body now than I was a month ago, and I could tell the difference.  And I did a bit of stretching, and the easiest thing seemed to be to go for some of the stretches we've done together in practice, some of the things I'd learned from Adriene, because after all, I know them now, right?  And then five or ten minutes later, after I'd decided to skip today entirely, I was in tabletop position moving into a twist and I thought to myself, _you know, if we're down here already anyway, we might as well at least see what the day's practice is._

And there it was, exactly what I needed.  For my body, which hurts more than I wish it did at my age, and can't bend or lift or move the way I want it to, but which _does_ bend and lift and feel and work as hard as it can, which has always done its best for me while I've tried to do my best for myself.  For my heart.

Today was a good day.

I had something meaningful stolen from me today, and it left me feeling vulnerable, confused, frustrated, angry, hurt. I don't understand how a stranger can see my property and think it can be theirs. And I've been telling everyone today what happened, and I really didn't want to do yoga because I knew I'd end up crying (again). But I always get something from this practice, and today I'm leaving with Adriene's words that maybe the nurturing I need comes from within. Everyone tells me oh no I'm sorry that happened, but no matter how many people say it, I don't feel better. It's still stolen. So I'll keep crying to release these emotions and I'll look inside to try and find the nurturing I need to get through it.

It's day 25 (check!) and I have something really special to share with you. I had a hard day, where I felt disappointed at myself and not content with a lot of things. Not only did I show that tiny little gesture of love to myself, but I also felt my breath slowly lifting my arms and lowering them, and so on... My arms on my chest, my chest breathing, my arms hugging me. It felt magical.

Growing up I had a very tough relationship with my body, it was all hate and no love. It was definitely conditioned by how my body never fit any canon of modern beauty and fit, the pressure I felt to be liked by my peers for what I looked like crushed me many times and so did the evil comments of young and adults alike. I started doing yoga daily more than a year ago ( a bit later with Adriene) and in this period of time, I felt the biggest change in my mindset. My body got more flexible and a bit stronger, without changing my weight or shape. But the biggest change happened in my mind when I finally learnt to love myself for who I am and started to let go of society imposed beauty canons. It's been a long and awaited journey but I'm glad I can finally be able to appreciate (most of the times) what my body does for me and how it looks like, too.
‚ÄúYou are love‚Äù

on day 25 I finally managed to wake up and do it in the morning. Even though i was used to an evening practice before. I  started 11 minutes after the upload but tomorrow i'll catch that magic moment :D I feel like i will still need an evening practice because I already created this habit of releasing the day, forgetting about work and going back to myself. But I think I'll just do one of the previous breath days :) I'm so glad I joined the 30 day journey this time. My goal in the beginning was to show up for myself without the focus being fitness, changing my body, losing weight or comparing myself to anyone. I just wanted a sole dedication of showing up every day no matter what - a habit. And I feel like it's really happening, it is becoming a habit. 3 days ago I stopped eating sugary stuff but it felt natural without an ounce of force, I suppose change can be gradual :) I love this community and I can't wait to see what's next. But I believe, for many of us, it will be a year of daily practice :)
